(EOF) analysis of the PDSI reveals a fairly linear
trend resulting from trends in precipitation and
surface temperature and an El Nino Southern
Oscillation (ENSO)-induced mode of mostly
interannual variations as the two leading
patterns. The global very dry areas, defined as PDSI
{\textless} -3.0, have more than doubled since the 1970s, with
a large jump in the early 1980s due to an
ENSO-induced precipitation decrease and a subsequent
expansion primarily due to surface warming, while
global very wet areas (PDSI {\textgreater} +3.0) declined
slightly during the 1980s. Together, the global land
areas in either very dry or very wet conditions have
increased from; 20{\%} to 38{\%} since 1972, with
surface warming as the primary cause after the
mid-1980s. These results provide observational
evidence for the increasing risk of droughts as
anthropogenic global warming progresses and produces
both increased temperatures and increased drying.},
