with broad impacts over the conterminous U.S. (1996,
1999-2002) were associated with North Atlantic
warming (positive AMO) and northeastern and tropical
Pacific cooling (negative PDO). Much of the
long-term predictability of drought frequency may
reside in the multidecadal behavior of the North
Atlantic Ocean. Should the current positive AMO
(warm North Atlantic) conditions persist into the
upcoming decade, we suggest two possible drought
scenarios that resemble the continental-scale
patterns of the 1930s (positive PDO) and 1950s
